V{{Infobox philosopher\u000a|region           = [[Western philosophy]]\u000a|era              = [[20th-century philosophy]]\u000a|image       =\u000a|image_size       =\u000a|caption     = \u000a|name             = Duncan Kennedy\u000a|birth_date       = {{birth year and age|1942}}\u000a|birth_place      = [[Washington, D.C.]]\u000a|death_date       = \u000a|school_tradition = Critical Theory\u000a|main_interests   = [[Legal philosophy]]\u000a|notable_ideas    = [[Critical legal studies|Critical Legal Studies movement]]\u000a|influences       = \u000a|influenced       = [[Louis Michael Seidman]], [[Gary Peller]]\u000a|signature        = \u000a}}\u000a\u000a'''Duncan Kennedy''' (born 1942) is the Carter Professor of General Jurisprudence at [[Harvard Law School]] and a founder of [[critical legal studies]] as movement and school of thought.\u000a\u000a==Education and early career==\u000a\u000aKennedy received an [[Bachelor of Arts|A.B.]] from [[Harvard College]] in 1964 and then worked for two years in the [[CIA]] operation that controlled the [[National Student Association]].<ref>See [http://duncankennedy.net/documents/A%20Semiotics%20of%20Critique.pdf Duncan Kennedy, ''Symposium: Afterword, A Semiotics of Critique,'' 22 Cardozo L. Rev. 1147, 1166-67 (2001).]\u000a</ref>  In 1966 he rejected his "cold war liberalism."<ref>''Id.'' at 1167.</ref>  He quit the CIA<ref>''Id.''</ref> and in 1970 earned an [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]] from [[Yale Law School]]. After completing a clerkship with [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Justice [[Potter Stewart]], Kennedy joined the Harvard Law School faculty, becoming a full professor in 1976. In March 2010 he received an Honoris Causa (honorary degree) Ph.D. title from the [[University of the Andes (Colombia)|University of the Andes]] in [[Colombia]].\u000a\u000aKennedy has been a member of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] since 1967. According to his own testimony, he has never forgotten to pay his dues.<ref>Duncan Kennedy, Harvard Law School Lecture, "Globalization of Legal Ideas and Ideology," April 14, 2011.</ref>\u000a\u000a==Academic work and influence==\u000aIn 1977, together with [[Karl Klare]], [[Mark Kelman]], [[Roberto Mangabeira Unger|Roberto Unger]], and other scholars, Kennedy established the [[critical legal studies|Critical Legal Studies movement]]. Outside legal academia, he is mostly known for his monograph ''[[Legal Education and the Reproduction of Hierarchy]]''*[http://www.duncankennedy.net/documents/Photo%20articles/Legal%20Education%20and%20the%20Reproduction%20of%20Hierarchy_J.%20Leg.%20Ed..pdf], famous for its trenchant critique of American legal education.\u000a\u000a==Bibliography==\u000a*''A Critique of Adjudication [fin de siècle]'', ([[Harvard University Press]], 1997)\u000a*''Sexy Dressing, etc.'', (Harvard University Press, 1993)\u000a*"Freedom and Constraint in Adjudication: A Critical Phenomenology," 36 ''Journal of Legal Education'' 518 (1986)\u000a*"Form and Substance in Private Law Adjudication," 89 ''[[Harvard Law Review]]'' 1685 (1976)\u000a*"A Semiotics of Critique," 22 ''Cardozo Law Review'' 1147 (2001)\u000a*"Thoughts on Coherence, Social Values and National Tradition in Private Law," in Hesselink, ed., ''The Politics of a European Civil Code'' ([[Kluwer Academic Publishers|Kluwer Law International]], Amsterdam, 2006)\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a*[[Critical legal studies]]\u000a*[[Indeterminacy debate in legal theory]]\u000a*[[List of deconstructionists]]\u000a*[[Philosophy of law]]\u000a\u000a==Notes==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a*[http://www.duncankennedy.net Duncan Kennedy's Personal Website]\u000a*[http://www.law.harvard.edu/faculty/directory/facdir.php?id=35 Duncan Kennedy's Harvard Law School Home Page]\u000a*[http://www.legalleft.org/?page_id=137 Duncan Kennedy debates [[Noah Feldman]] in March 2008 at Harvard Law School, as part of a series on "Confronting Empire"]\u000a*{{YouTube|eXICJnTmiNs|Duncan Kennedy at the University of the Andes}}, lecture on law and economics\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Kennedy, Duncan}}\u000a[[Category:1942 births]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:Critical legal studies]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard Law School faculty]]\u000a[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of law]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]
